  "research_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<h3 class=\"research-heading\">Overview</h3>\n<p class=\"research-text\">The <strong>Scholia-Hymn III</strong> (Σχόλια εἰς Ὕμνον Γ΄) are ancient prose commentaries on Callimachus’s <strong>Hymn to Artemis</strong>. These scholia, comprising 18 discrete notes in the transmitted text, exemplify Alexandrian scholarship by elucidating the hymn’s mythological references, rare vocabulary, and geographical allusions. They function as a key pedagogical aid for interpreting Callimachus’s learned and complex poetic style.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"research-section\">\n<h3 class=\"research-heading\">Content</h3>\n<p class=\"research-text\">The scholia address several exegetical topics:</p>\n<ul class=\"research-list\">\n<li class=\"research-item\"><strong>Mythological Explanation:</strong> Identifying figures and stories.</li>\n<li class=\"research-item\"><strong>Lexicography:</strong> Defining archaic or rare words.</li>\n<li class=\"research-item\"><strong>Geographical Reference:</strong> Clarifying place names.</li>\n<li class=\"research-item\"><strong>Textual Criticism:</strong> Noting variant readings.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"research-section\">\n<h3 class=\"research-heading\">Transmission</h3>\n<p class=\"research-text\">Preserved in medieval manuscripts such as the 11th-century <strong>Laurentianus plut. 32.9</strong>, these notes are a condensed compilation of earlier Hellenistic and Roman scholarship, transmitted and abbreviated within the Byzantine tradition alongside the primary poetic text.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"research-section\">\n<h3 class=\"research-heading\">Significance</h3>\n<p class=\"research-text\">The scholia are crucial for modern understanding of Callimachus, preserving fragments of lost commentaries and documenting ancient interpretative practices. They remain a fundamental resource for editors and scholars resolving textual difficulties and reconstructing the mythological erudition of Hellenistic poetry.</p>\n</div>",
